Diagnostic remarks.
C. maculatus

is recognizable by the shape of the male cercus, armed with only one inner tooth (
Fig. 7E
), the presence of a wide, dark band extending from the frons to the base of tegmina, and small dark markings on the tegmen (the markings are not as extensive as in 

C. iris

). Both green and brown forms of the species are common but only macropterous forms occur in the region (
Fig. 7F
).
